<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 94 / Finance and the Family: Directors' transactions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By COLIN ROGERS, Inside Track
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The market soars to unexploded heights and we wait to see what directors
will do. Some do nothing much, some sell a little to take profits, others
continue to deal for personal financial planning reasons.
Nobo Group produces office equipment. In the second week of January, the
company announced interim results strongly ahead of the same period last
year. The share price has moved up on the back of it so the sale of 200,000
shares each by Peter Kent, the non-executive chairman, and Reginald Barr,
the chief executive, is not surprising. Each director retains considerable
quantities of stock. Sales should aid market liquidity.
Thomas French &amp; Sons, the home decoration company, appears in both the sale
and buy columns. Final results were announced at the beginning of January
and M Snapes was appointed as a new chief executive. He then bought 100,000
shares. The chairman and erstwhile managing director, Thomas French, sold
100,000 shares to Snapes and sold the other 250,000 shares for a beneficial
trust.
A Beckman Plc is involved in both textile converting and merchanting and
property investment. Melvin Lawson, an executive director bought 120,000
shares for 55p, increasing his holding to over 900,000.
