FT  22 JAN 94 / Markets: Card spending up - At a glance
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Debit cards are widely regarded as a replacement for cheques, according to
the Credit Card Research Group, and are used for cheaper purchases than
credit cards. The most popular outlets for the use of debit cards are
supermarkets, off licences and petrol stations, while credit cards
expenditure is more widely spread across the retail sector. Total plastic
card spending in the UK was Pounds 49.6bn in 1993 up from Pounds 43.9bn in
1992.
