<PROFILE>_AN-EAWARAC1FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940122
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 94 / London Stock Exchange: Redland strong
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, JOEL KIBAZO, STEVE THOMPSON and CLARE GASCOIGNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Building materials group Redland was one of the FT-SE 100's best performers,
the shares rising 23 to 622p, after stories that the shares were being given
a strong push by Cazenove, the company's own stockbroker. Cazenove wields
immense influence in the stockmarket but adheres strictly to a long-standing
policy of not commenting on its corporate and agency broking activities
'There has been some persistent and sizeable demand for Redland shares,'
said one building sector specialist, who added that the share price may well
have been pushed ahead by recent market stories that a series of Europe-wide
interest rate cuts could be in the pipeline.
A quiet day in pharmaceuticals was dominated by a positive trading statement
from Zeneca, up 10 to 818p. 'Not a dramatic bit of news' was how one analyst
described it, although others were more complimentary; Mr Nigel Barnes at
Hoare Govett said Zeneca and Glaxo, flat at 661p, were the only two stocks
that were still attractive in terms of yield. 'The rest of the sector has
been looking a bit tired,' he said.
SmithKline Beecham 'A' shares were up 4 at 436p, little affected by
NatWest's Securities issue of 50m warrants. Mr Nick Conington at NatWest
said that over the long term, the stock appeared undervalued. 'It's too
early to call the stock a buy - we have to wait and see,' he said.
Among supermarket groups, Park Food saw improved sales and earnings and the
shares climbed 3 to 294p, after touching 303p. The majors were weak on a
combination of profit-taking and lingering concerns over the industry's
direction in the wake of Tesco's trading statement this week. The company
cut its capital expenditure, made provisions for property write-downs and
signalled its intention to grow dividends, in the face of continuing margin
pressure. How market leader J Sainsbury will respond to the Tesco move is
the question being pondered in food retail circles, and it was concern over
this that saw the shares come off 11 to 460p. Tesco fell 5 to 243 1/2 p.
Food manufacturers were subdued, although Hazlewood declined 5 to 174p on
talk of poor Christmas sales.
Stores were mixed although Great Universal Stores surged 16 to 629p amid a
market rumour of an impending warrant to be issued by a leading securities
house. Talk of healthy margins at Marks and Spencer underpinned the shares,
up 7 1/2 at 459 1/2 p. WH Smith jumped 16 to 545p ahead of results next
week, while MFI Furniture, also reporting, slipped 1 1/2 to 167p. Despite
market talk of weak margins over Christmas, brokers close to the company are
confident of profits above the average of market forecasts. The range is
Pounds 18-25m.
Shares in business services group Inchcape, moved sharply ahead after Robert
Fleming reiterated its buy recommendation on the stock. The move follows
Thursday's recommendation from US investment bank Goldman Sachs and the
shares jumped 34 to 589p, on volume of 2.9m. Mr Mike Smith at Fleming said
the stock had been left behind due to uncertainty about trading at Gestetner
in which it has a 15 per cent stake and nerves about next Thursday's trading
update. Gestetner closed 12 ahead at 171p, following favourable comment on
its results.
European demand continued for British Steel following a Credit Lyonnais
recommendation earlier this week. The shares hardened 1 1/2 to 128 1/2 p as
turnover soared to 27m.
</TEXT>
