<PROFILE>_AN-EAWARACYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940122
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 94 / London Stock Exchange: New peaks on the Footsie following
GDP data - Market report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK stock market put its hopes of an early base rate cut back on the
shelf yesterday and moved to new peaks after the latest data on gross
domestic product, money supply and bank lending data indicated further
strengthening in the domestic economy. The FT-SE Index, led by the stock
index market, challenged the 3,500 mark to establish a new trading high
before closing 14.2 up on the day at 3,484.2.
The announcement that GDP had grown by 0.7 per cent over the final quarter
of last year brought a confident response from Mr Kenneth Clarke, the UK
chancellor of the exchequer, who repeated his budget forecast that the UK
economy will expand by 2.5 per cent this year.
Equities were uncertain at first, in spite of a firm performances overnight
in Far Eastern markets and on Wall Street. Second line stocks traded more
calmly as the interest returned to the Footsie, futures-related stocks.
Satisfaction with the economic data was quickly reflected in the futures
market where the March contract on the Footsie raced above the 3,500 mark
again. The FT-SE Index itself turned from its early fall of nearly 7 points
to touch 3,496.1, for a net rise of more than 26 points.
But the futures contract came off, and that proved to be the peak of the day
for share prices, although a firm start to the new session on Wall Street,
when the Dow Average broke through 3,900, buoyed London at the close.
The FT-SE 100 Share Index has risen by 183.6 points, or about 2.5 per cent
this week in good turnover. Seaq volume slipped to 979.7m shares, still at
the higher end of daily averages for the past 18 months. On Thursday, Seaq
volume of 1.1bn shares returned a retail worth of Pounds 2.53bn, around
twice recent daily averages.
But much of the excitement at mid-week came from the massive rise on the Mid
250 Index which has gained nearly 5 per cent since last Friday. Investors
have been buying Mid 250 stocks because they are on lower rating than the
blue chips which captured the buying interest in the dramatic advance in the
stock market before Christmas.
London was helped by strength in the leading oil stocks, on the back of US
markets, and by another round of substantial gains in stocks linked to Far
Eastern markets.
Traders said that buyers were highly stock selective, and are now shying
away from the highly rated blue chip stocks which are on prospective
earnings multiples of 25 times.
Base rate hopes were resurrected this week after news that retail sales
dipped last month, but the London market has been discouraged by the absence
of any move from the Bundesbank. The president of the German central bank
said yesterday that it appeared right to hold interest rate policy 'steady'
for now.
Although confidence on UK inflation prospects remains high, bonds slipped
lower yesterday as prices were readjusted at the end of a very successful
week for the sector. Short-dated issues recorded small losses, with the
longer end down by around  1/4 of a point. Index-linked followed the trend
of the long dated conventional government bonds.
Overseas and domestic demand for gilts, which has sustained the market this
week, was reduced yesterday although the GDP and money supply data was
regarded as within the bracket of market estimates.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
