<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 94 / International Company News: Caterpillar result boosts shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Caterpillar, the US heavy plant and machinery maker, continued
their upward surge yesterday as the company reported another quarter of
strong recovery. They added Dollars 2 5/8 to Dollars 96 5/8 by midday.
Fourth-quarter losses of Dollars 2m the previous year turned into after-tax
profits of Dollars 148m this time, or Dollars 119m after an extraordinary
loss of Dollars 29m for the early retirement of some high interest rate
debt.
Earnings per share were Dollars 1.46 before the extraordinary item and
Dollars 1.17 after it, compared with a loss per share of 2 cents last time.
Caterpillar's share price has nearly doubled over the last year in response
to the sharp recovery in the company's financial performance.
Its profits are strongly linked to the economic cycle because its equipment
sells best when public and private sectors are spending on construction and
expansion.
The biggest single factor behind the latest quarter's turnround was a 16 per
cent increase in turnover to Dollars 3.2bn, with three-quarters of the
increase coming from higher physical sales and the other quarter from better
prices.
Nearly all the improvement took place in the US, where economic growth
stimulated demand. Volumes outside the US were more or less flat.
For the year as a whole, Caterpillar recorded a 14 per cent increase in
sales to Dollars 11.2bn, with higher demand from US industry more than
offsetting moderate declines in Europe, Africa, the Middle East and Latin
America.
Net profits were Dollars 681m excluding the fourth-quarter's extraordinary
loss of Dollars 29m. Last year the company lost Dollars 218m, or Dollars
2.4bn after a Dollars 2.2bn charge for accounting changes.
Higher demand world-wide is expected to bring further profits growth this
year.
</TEXT>
