<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 94 / UK Company News: The end is nigh for Bank of Edinburgh
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bank of Edinburgh, a vehicle set up by three years ago to acquire small and
medium-sized building societies, is close to being wound up at a substantial
loss after its failure to take over any societies.
Bank of Edinburgh has been searching for new owners after its shareholders,
led by Scottish Amicable, asked to withdraw following the collapse of its
attempt to take over the Heart of England Building Society last March.
The Bank of England disclosed yesterday that the bank had given up its
banking licence. This was used to raise a small amount of deposits, and to
earn money by lending the bank's Pounds 5.9m capital and liabilities to
other banks.
Mr Russell Frith, finance director of the bank, said it had not yet decided
to close. 'We have decided that we must either find a new parent, or return
the money to the existing shareholders.'
In its last published accounts, for 1992, the bank had some Pounds 5.2m of
capital remaining from the Pounds 8m it drew from institutional investors.
The failure of the Heart of England bid led to a Pounds 1.58m write-down of
capital.
After repaying deposits to about 60 depositors, the bank is expected to be
able to repay only about half the capital it drew. Apart from Scottish
Amicable, other investors include life insurance companies and venture
capital groups.
The bank gained a licence when it took over the banking arm of Goode
Durrant, the financial services company, in 1992. Its original intention was
to acquire a number of societies and merge them into a single financial
services group.
</TEXT>
