<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 94 / UK Company News: Single premium side ahead at Allied Dunbar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Allied Dunbar, one of the 10 largest UK life insurance companies, yesterday
announced its new business figures for 1993, showing steady growth in single
premium business.
The figures reflected the pattern elsewhere in the life industry, with
single premium business gaining, while annual premium business fell back, as
economic uncertainties such as fear of unemployment have made people more
reluctant to commit themselves to long-term policies.
Allied Dunbar's new single premiums rose sharply from Pounds 631m in 1992 to
Pounds 865m.
Within that total, however, there was a switch of business, as single
premium investments rose by 79 per cent to Pounds 548.6m (Pounds 307m), but
single premium pensions fell slightly from Pounds 323.5m to Pounds 315.8m.
New annual premiums also dropped slightly, from Pounds 162.1m to Pounds
158.5m.
New critical illness cover almost doubled, from Pounds 887m in 1992 to
Pounds 1.62bn. The company said the rise suggested a market trend towards
buying life and critical illness together, rather than buying just life
cover.
The company, which is a subsidiary of BAT Industries, attributed much of the
overall increase to its direct sales force, which numbers some 4,200 sales
agents.
National Mutual Life, a pensions specialist which markets entirely through
independent financial advisers, said yesterday that its new business had
risen to Pounds 236.1m, compared with Pounds 133.9m in 1992.
There was a particularly steep increase in its single premium new business
from Pounds 87.5m to Pounds 151.8m. Its regular premium new business also
rose, from Pounds 16m to Pounds 27.2m.
</TEXT>
