FT  22 JAN 94 / Financial advisers warn over PIA
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The National Federation of Independent Financial Advisers yesterday warned
that it might support calls for statutory regulation of financial services,
Alison Smith writes.
Mr Bill Raynes, chairman, said the federation did not want statutory
regulation but was not prepared to accept the version of self-regulation
proposed for the personal investment authority (PIA).
The latest controversy was sparked by the PIA's decision that only nine of
its 19-strong board should be working in the industry. This prompted the
resignation from the board of Mr Jim Stretton, deputy managing director of
Standard Life, who argued that this could not amount to self-regulation.
Mr Garry Heath, federation chief executive, said: 'Too many product
providers have locked the door of their closet and despite Jim Stretton's
principled stand have not come out and been counted.'
He added, however, that the federation had dropped plans to apply for
judicial review into the PIA board structure.
