<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JAN 94 / Sky's the limit for soaraway Kelvin
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'Exclusive: the Queen Mother's killer corgi Ranger has savaged Fergie's
dog,' says the main article on the front page of this morning's Sun.
Students of tabloid journalism will instantly recognise the style of Mr
Kelvin Mackenzie, editor for 13 years.
But they will have to turn to the bottom of Page 2 to learn that it is one
of the last issues to be edited by him.
The archetypal tabloid editor, who rarely appears on television, is leaving
what used to be called Fleet Street to be managing director of British Sky
Broadcasting.
Mr Gus Fischer, chief executive of the paper's parent company News
International, said Mr MacKenzie deserved such a career move. 'He is very
smart,' Mr Fischer added. 'He can also be serious, very serious.' At BSkyB -
in which Pearson, owner of the Financial Times has a stake - he will join Mr
Sam Chisholm, chief executive, one of the few people in the UK media who is
every bit as direct in his language as Mr MacKenzie.
Mr Chisholm, who will be showing 47-year old Mr MacKenzie the ropes from
next Monday, said last night: 'The great thing about Kelvin is he is a
highly creative, very energetic man with a great deal of flair and
imagination.'
Mr Stuart Higgins, aged 37, the deputy editor of The Sun and acting editor
of the News of the World, will become only the third editor of the paper
since its relaunch by Mr Rupert Murdoch in 1969.
Mr MacKenzie was saying little last night about his new job. He did issue an
uncharacteristically bland quote about having had the best job in British
journalism for the past 13 years and was now on his way to one of the most
exciting challenges in television. Other than that he could not be
distracted from editing this morning's paper.
Independent decision, Page 8
</TEXT>
