<DATE>940121
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 94 / International Company News: Bankers Trust turns in surge for
quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Bankers Trust, the US commercial bank, reported a further surge in profits
from trading in financial markets in the final three months of last year, at
a time when easing volatility in European markets cut into trading profits
at other big US banks.
Like JP Morgan, which reported its 1993 earnings last week, the bank boosted
its trading profits in the emerging country debt markets, and bolstering
dwindling income from the European currency and interest rate markets.
The value of debt securities issued by a number of Latin American and
emerging Asian countries rose strongly last year on stronger economic
fundamentals and demand from US investors for high-yielding investments.
Income from trading rose to Dollars 449m in the last quarter of 1993, up
from Dollars 101m a year before and ahead of the record Dollars 431m of the
previous quarter.
In all, trading income contributed 36 per cent of the revenues in the latest
quarter. Further unspecified trading profits, made in interest rate markets
and accounted for as net interest income, further lifted this portion.
The results boosted the bank's net income in the final three months to
Dollars 279m, or Dollars 3.25 a share, up from Dollars 133m, restated as
Dollars 1.49 a share, the year before and well ahead of analysts' estimates.
Earnings per share calculations for the latest and previous periods were
adjusted to take account of equity-related items like stock options the bank
has issued, diluting the final eps figure.
After-tax profits for the year as a whole reached Dollars 1.07bn, or Dollars
12.40 a share, up from Dollars 639m, or Dollars 7.22 a share, in 1992,
before various accounting changes in both periods.
Both Bankers Trust and JP Morgan have shaken off the revenue slowdown faced
by other US banks by moving heavily into trading activities and growing
their fee and commission-related business.
</TEXT>
