<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 94 / Redwood accused of being cereal killer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A parish boundary runs through a field of winter barley on Mr Roger Jones's
100-hectare farm which borders the Rhymney Valley in Gwent, south Wales. The
barley on one side will earn him Pounds 191 a hectare in aid from Brussels.
On the other it will be eligible for Pounds 98 a hectare at the most.
'It doesn't make sense,' he said. 'It's all the same land.'
Mr Jones's problem arises from government proposals to divide Wales into two
regions to determine the amount of compensation that arable farmers will be
paid now Brussels has reduced its support prices.
The government is under heavy pressure from Wales's 4,000 cereal growers to
drop the complex two-tier system, which is based on the amount of land under
cereal production in each of the country's 1,000 parishes. The farmers say
it is unfair and divisive.
Mr Owen Williams, a neighbour of Mr Jones, grows cereals in the Rhymney
Valley. Because he is in a mainly hilly parish that produces under 50
hectares of winter cereals - the cut-off figure - he will qualify only for
the lower payments. 'It's absolutely ludicrous,' he said. 'Our farm was left
out of the 'less favoured area' grants because it was considered too
productive.'
Mr Williams produces more than 7 tonnes of cereals a hectare, much the same
as Mr Jones a mile away. 'Our land is capable of growing crops equal to
anything they can grow in England,' he adds.
Like Mr Jones, he has appealed to the Welsh Office about the decision, which
he said would cost him between Pounds 4,000 and Pounds 5,000.
Mr Frank Leguen de Lacroix, a European Commission agriculture official
invited to Wales by the National Farmers' Union earlier this month, is
raising the matter with UK officials. He said he was puzzled by the scheme,
which appeared to set one grower against another.
Mr John Redwood, Welsh secretary, proposed dividing Wales last year after
Welsh arable farmers objected to being paid less compensation than those in
England.
The aim was to bring more Welsh growers into the higher payment category
used in England. Mr Redwood said at the time that the plan was the most
equitable possible.
But the NFU, which represents growers in both England and Wales, wants the
government to start again. It says the two countries should be treated as a
single region, with the same payments for all farms.
Redistributing the total aid package among English and Welsh farmers would
entail a cut of only about 52p a tonne for English producers, says the
union. 'The alternative, with the Gatt cuts coming, could be the end of
cereal growing for those who are left so far behind,' it said.
A government announcement is expected shortly. The farmers suspect Mr
Redwood may abandon the plan and return to a simple division between England
and Wales. They resent that just as much.
</TEXT>
<XX>
