<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 94 / Milk board may sell two offshoots
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Milk Marketing Board could be forced to hive off its artificial
insemination section and its milk testing business to get government
approval for its plans to transform itself into a farmers' co-operative.
Genus, which provides advice and semen for breeding dairy cattle, could be
floated off as an unlisted company or made into a government body. The
business had a turnover last year of Pounds 35m with pre-tax profits of
Pounds 4m.
However, the future of National Milk Records is more problematic because it
is closely integrated with the board's daily activities, according to Mr
Andrew Dare, chief executive. He will head Milk Marque, as the new
co-operative will be known, when the Pounds 3.3bn milk market in England and
Wales is opened to competition later this year.
Mr Dare said: 'It would be quite a headache to split it off.'
The flotation of Dairy Crest, the board's processing division, has been
delayed from next month to June or July because of government objections
over plans to reorganise the board.
Options for separating both Genus and National Milk Records are under
review.
The board must decide by Monday whether to hive off both business units to
satisfy government concerns about its dominant position in the market. Mr
Dare will meet officials from the agriculture ministry on Monday to complete
changes to plans for turning the board into Milk Marque.
Government queries over the board's plans have delayed the introduction of
competition into the milk market from April to either the beginning of
August or October.
Mr Dare said: 'I want to be able to prove that a properly managed and
properly financed farmers' co-op can succeed. We have to get it right now.'
Mr Dare has agreed with the government that the new body will have a capital
base of Pounds 37.5m excluding Genus and National Milk Records. Apart from
their future, all of the government's misgivings over the reorganisation
have been cleared up, he said.
</TEXT>
