<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 94 / Gas users predict tighter regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Gas Consumers Council has predicted that regulation of the gas supply
industry will need to be tightened as the domestic monopoly controlled by
British Gas is opened to full competition in 1998.
Mr Ian Powe, council director, will tell a conference today that Ofgas, the
industry regulator, will have to oversee the sector's transition away from
the present regulatory regime under which government bodies from the
Department of Trade and Industry to the Office of Fair Trading have
occasionally conflicting roles in the sector to one of 'controlled
competition' in which Ofgas should be the sole authority.
He adds: 'Whether we like it or not, we are going to see more regulation,
not less, as competition grows.'
He says the main challenge for Ofgas will be to hold down prices to the
consumer while managing the transition of the industry to a strict
cost-related structure to encourage competition and consumer choice.
Mr Powe attacks British Gas in his speech, accusing it of 'scaremongering'
during last year's debate on the future of the industry.
He rejects the notion that consumers should pay for British Gas' corporate
reorganisation years, and warns against relaxing the present price-setting
arrangement, based on on the retail price index minus five percentage
points.
