FT  21 JAN 94 / Sale-of-goods laws to be reviewed
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
England's ancient sale-of-goods laws, which set out the ways in which a
purchaser can get good title to goods bought in good faith from someone who
does not own them, are to be reviewed, the government announced yesterday.
A consultation paper proposes replacing the detailed rules in the 1979 Sale
of Goods Act with a broad principle that where goods have been entrusted to
someone by the owner an innocent purchaser should get good title, abolishing
the rule on sales in market overt (ancient markets), and extending the
protection given to purchasers of cars on hire purchase to other goods.
