<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 94 / Top Civil servants court industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Senior company executives are to be told next week that they may be able to
boost their business prospects - by employing a civil servant.
The message will be delivered by Sir Robin Butler, cabinet secretary and
head of the civil service, at a private lunch in London on Tuesday for
directors of 17 big companies.
The gathering is aimed at helping Whitehall officials expand their view of
the world by giving more of them a taste of life in industry through
part-time advisory jobs.
To overcome any scepticism about the commercial acumen of civil servants,
Sir Robin will also stress the role of Whitehall officials in giving a fresh
view of business problems and in helping companies to build up sales and
profits.
The lunch has been arranged by the Whitehall and Industry Group, a charity
funded by the government and 64 big companies including Midland Bank,
Cadbury Schweppes, Courtaulds and British Telecommunications.
An official on the initiative said: 'Companies do not generally come
knocking on our doors asking to employ civil servants. You have to do some
persuading to tell them what the potential benefits can be.'
Mr John Sacher, a director of Marks and Spencer who is chairman of the
Whitehall and Industry Group, said that many civil servants who had worked
part-time in companies had proved 'extremely constructive'. He added: 'We
are talking about high-flyers who have a lot to contribute to strategic
issues.'
The lunch fits in with efforts by Mr John Major, the prime minister, to
promote a more sympathetic view of wealth creation by officials across
Whitehall.
The main aim of the lunch is to increase the number of civil servants
working part-time as non-executive members of subsidiary boards from about
50 to possibly 100.
</TEXT>
