<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 94 / Sellafield workers face ban on voting in council
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Copeland Borough Council, the local authority responsible for planning
decisions relating to British Nuclear Fuels' Sellafield plant, has received
legal advice that councillors who work for BNF should not vote on
applications made by their employer.
Until now Copeland councillors employed by BNF have been allowed to vote on
its applications for permission for sometimes controversial developments at
the west Cumbria nuclear-waste reprocessing site.
But in response to a Copeland council request for legal guidance Mr Steven
Cockman QC, a specialist in local government law, has advised that
councillors should declare an interest and not vote on applications by their
employer or their spouses' employer.
If Labour-controlled Copeland implements this advice, it would change the
balance of power on the key planning and services committee, where four of
the seven Labour members are BNF employees.
Their withdrawal when BNF applications were being considered would leave
three Labour members, four Conservatives and one independent.
Nine of Copeland's 53 councillors are Sellafield employees of BNF, the
area's dominant employer. They include Labour and Conservative members.
Several others are married to BNF employees. Legal guidance was sought
during a council review of its standing orders. A decision on whether to
implement the QC's advice will be taken following a debate at the next full
council meeting next month.
Some councillors are unhappy at the proposal, believing their workplace
experience gives them useful knowledge to contribute to decisions.
Under the Department of the Environment's national code, councillors should
normally declare an interest and not vote when they have a pecuniary or
other direct interest. But the department said it was up to councils how
they interpreted this guidance.
</TEXT>
