<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 94 / Labour leads attack on homes reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour joined forces with some of Britain's leading pressure groups
yesterday to attack the government's proposals to reform the allocation of
council housing to the homeless.
The proposals, which came in a consultation paper issued by Sir George
Young, the housing minister, would abolish the rule allowing people classed
as 'statutorily homeless' - many of whom are single mothers - to receive an
automatic right to a council house.
Under the proposals all applicants for council accommodation would have to
join a waiting list. However, local authorities would single out people who
were in emergency need of housing and place them in temporary accommodation.
But these people would have to compete with everyone else on the waiting
list before receiving a secured tenancy. The 'fast track' by which these
people now acquire council accommodation in perpetuity would be abolished.
The reforms could disadvantage single mothers who make up some 45 per cent
of the statutorily homeless, and now receive priority.
Mr Jack Straw, shadow environment secretary, attacked the policy, saying
that a chronic shortage of affordable homes had created the problem.
He added: 'With Labour, 100,000 new homes were built for rent by councils
and housing associations. Under the Tories that has been cut to a third.'
Ms Sheila McKechnie, director of Shelter, the housing charity, claimed that
the new system would leave families moving from one temporary home to
another until a secure tenancy could be found.
'Do we really want to see families who don't know where their children will
be at school next term or whether they will be able to get to their job, if
they have one, and what the future holds for them?' she asked.
However, Sir George said yesterday that the proposals were aimed at curbing
the practice by which people living with their parents left home, declared
themselves 'statutorily homeless' and received accommodation ahead of other
applicants.
This, he said, was to the dis-advantage of people who stayed with parents
while joining a housing association waiting list. Under the new proposals,
people who leave their parents' home would not be treated as an emergency.
Sir George also said that he would be looking at ways for local authorities
to offer applicants rented accommodation in the private sector. This would
be paid for by housing benefit up to a certain level, possibly topped up by
a local authority grant.
</TEXT>
