<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 94 / Pensions rule withdrawn in tendering row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Department of the Environment has climbed down over new regulations
which would have forced private companies taking over local authority
contracts to offer employees 'broadly comparable' pensions.
Contractors claimed the ruling would make it impossible for small companies
to bid for council business, as they would not have the resources to match
public-sector pensions, which are usually index-linked.
After meeting contractors on Wednesday, Mr Tony Baldry, the environment
minister, decided to withdraw the department's pensions advice, which was
issued to the press on Tuesday, and was due to be announced in the Commons
today.
Mr Baldry will now restrict his statement to the Commons today to the
Transfer of Undertakings (Public Employees) regulations, known as Tupe,
which also affect local authority contracting.
The department's change of heart was attacked by contractors, local
authorities and unions.
Mr Cliff Davis-Coleman of Clause 26, a contractors' lobby group, described
the position as 'chaos', and predicted that the pensions provisions would
eventually be enforced, as similar rulings had been made regarding
contracting out from the National Health Service.
The Association of Direct Labour Organisations said competition would be
distorted if contractors were not required to offer the same employment
package to employees, and claimed the environment department's original
guidance was correct.
The department said that the decision had been taken because it needed to
consult other departments over the pensions issue, which is covered by the
Employment Protection (Consolidation) Act of 1978.
Mr Gummer will also announce today that where a local authority believes
that Tupe applies but a contractor does not, the authority can, after taking
legal advice, properly decide not to proceed with the tender.
Mr Davis-Coleman said this ruling would mean 'the end of compulsory
competitive tendering'. If Tupe applies to a particular contract, a
contractor taking over council work is obliged to keep the existing
workforce, on the same pay and conditions, and cannot save money by cutting
pay.
</TEXT>
