<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 94 / Branson lottery bid in place soon
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Richard Branson's Lottery Foundation is expected to announce within the
next few days that all its financing is in place to mount a bid to run the
National Lottery.
There was some speculation that the foundation might have difficulty raising
the capital because all the profits from the lottery would go to a
charitable foundation.
Agreement on financing has already been reached in principle and the legal
details are set to be tied up by next week.
The foundation, co-founded by Mr Branson, Virgin chairman, and Lord Young,
the former trade and industry secretary, is expected to be one of eight
bidders for the national licence.
At the formal launch of the foundation yesterday, the organisation published
an opinion poll saying that 72 per cent of the British public wanted all the
profits from the lottery to go to good causes. Just 23 per cent believed the
operating company should keep profits for itself. Around 64 per cent said
they would be more likely to play the lottery if the profits went to good
causes.
Bids have to be in by February 14, and it is estimated that in three or four
years the lottery could have annual revenues of between Pounds 3bn and
Pounds 4bn.
</TEXT>
