<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 94 / Halifax may enter rented sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Halifax, Britain's biggest mortgage lender, might be prepared to become a
private landlord if the government offered financial incentives to encourage
the rented sector, Mr Mike Blackburn, the society's chief executive, said
yesterday.
Mr Blackburn, addressing a Council of Mortgage Lenders conference in
Edinburgh, accused the government of turning its back on the housing market.
Tax allowances for homeowners and funding for social housing were being
reduced simultaneously, reversing almost 50 years of postwar policy.
He said: 'Households need further choice than simply between owning their
homes and moving into socially rented accommodation. In other countries this
is provided by private rented housing. In the UK this effectively does not
exist.' Private rented housing had fallen to just 9 per cent of the UK
housing market - 6 per cent in Scotland.
Mr Blackburn said that while the 1988 Housing Act had 'swept away' most of
the controls on renting that had been important factors in its decline
without subsidy it remained financially unattractive.
He said Halifax might consider entering the private rented market if it
became more commercially attractive, 'possibly through the ownership of a
company providing such accommodation'.
He added: 'It would hopefully be profitable and further enhance our
reserves. Most importantly it would help maintain our links with potential
borrowers providing them with rented accommodation for the early years of
their housing careers, before they take on a mortgage.'
Halifax said it would favour tax allowances rather than grants.
The society said that private renting could 'become an important new market
for our commercial lending'. It added: 'We would like to see potential
borrowers given more choice of tenure.'
</TEXT>
