<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 94 / WDA to be sued for unfair dismissal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A former senior executive of the Welsh Development Agency, who was sacked in
the wake of scathing criticisms of the agency by a Commons committee, is
claiming unfair dismissal.
Mr Michael Henry, executive director of corporate services, was dismissed in
October after a report by an independent inquiry set up by Mr David
Rowe-Beddoe, the WDA's newly-appointed chairman, in response to condemnation
by the public accounts committee.
'I've been made a scapegoat by the WDA,' Mr Henry said yesterday. 'I would
like an opportunity to state my case and I am determined to clear my name.'
Mr Henry, who managed the agency's Pounds 165m annual budget, is to bring
his case to an industrial tribunal supported by Unison, the public services
union. The union said a separate action for alleged defamation was 'under
active consideration'.
The WDA said it had referred the matter to its lawyers.
Mr Henry, now a self-employed accountant, had been with the agency since
1978 and was an executive director for six years. He was not a board member.
Together with Dr Gwyn Jones, the WDA's then chairman, and Mr Philip Head,
the chief executive, he was questioned by the Commons committee which
subsequently said the 'top echelons' of the agency had 'presided over a
catalogue of serious and inexcusable breaches of expected standards of
control and accountability'.
</TEXT>
