<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 94 / DTI demands changes to pension scheme regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Department of Trade and Industry yesterday called for several changes to
pension scheme regulation in its long-awaited report into the dealings of
mini-conglomerate Bestwood.
The company was wound up in June 1990 following the misappropriation of more
than Pounds 700,000 by its former chairman and chief executive, Mr Tony
Cole. Mr Cole also effected the removal of more than Pounds 900,000 from the
pension scheme of a Bestwood subsidiary, British Drilling and Freezing, over
several years. Most of that was eventually repaid although the scheme lost
about Pounds 300,000.
Most of the DTI's recommendations have also been suggested by a government
panel which was set up following the collapse of the Maxwell pension
schemes.
In particular, the DTI urges restrictions on the level of employer-related
investment by pension schemes. It also urges the appointment of at least one
independent trustee to the trustee boards of occupational schemes, a
recommendation rejected by the government's advisory panel.
The DTI report, which covers events from 1985 to 1989, explains how Mr Cole
and his associates were able to remove assets from the pension scheme and
use them to invest in companies in which they had a personal interest. The
removal of funds, says the report, was carried out through a
Bestwood-controlled fund management company, Atlanta Fund Managers, which
was the appointed investment manager for the pension scheme in June 1986.
In its conclusions, the DTI says that Mr Cole acted improperly 'in causing
AFM systematically to breach the restrictions laid down in relation to
investments'. He also acted improperly in causing certain investments
acquired by AFM from Glen International - the company controlled by
financier Mr Terry Ramsden - to be put through to the BDF pension scheme,
thus avoiding leaving AFM with losses. Also, he failed to see that trustees
of the pension scheme were properly informed of the investments.
Meanwhile, the two Best-wood directors who were pension scheme trustees  -
Mr Charles Wilkinson and Mr Jeremy Colson, group finance director - were
criticised 'for not ensuring that the abuse stopped'. Mr Colson 'wrongly
persuaded the trustees to lend Pounds 600,000 to Bestwood at a time when he
knew it was having difficulty in obtaining funds'.
The DTI report notes that when Bestwood acquired the 75.4 per cent of BDF
which it did not own in March 1986, the pension scheme's assets, at roughly
Pounds 5m, were more than twice its liabilities. 'The purchase price took
into account the surplus as a potential asset of Bestwood.'
However the trustees were unable to extract cash from the scheme without the
permission of the Superannuation Funds Office. They never formally sought
permission to do so.
Moreover, the DTI report explains how pension scheme assets were used to buy
shares in companies in which Best-wood directors held direct interests
although the employee trustees were never informed of these connections
between the directors.
By June 1988, the market value of the assets of the pension scheme had
fallen to Pounds 2.8m from just under Pounds 6m in June 1986.
Meanwhile, some assets disappeared from the pension scheme as loans. Some
Pounds 300,000 went as loans to stockbrokers Guy Puckle with whom Mr Cole
had an account. The loans were shown on the books of the pension scheme as
'cash on deposit'.
By June 1988 a further Pounds 359,000 of scheme assets was in unit trusts
managed by AFM. In turn, these unit trusts invested assets in other
companies connected with Mr Cole or his associates, in violation of unit
trust regulations.
In addition, of the pension scheme's holdings in quoted UK equities, the
largest portion was in shares of Bestwood itself or in the shares of other
companies in which Mr Cole or his associates had an interest.
</TEXT>
